\chapter{Creole and Cajun Personal Networks}
  \label{chap:networks}
  So far, the associations between realizations of subject pronouns and ethnicity have made it clear that subject pronouns can be used to identify a speaker's racialized ethnicity.
  Despite the regularity of these associations, however, some speakers showed exceptions to the pattern.
  Elizabeth Naquin, for instance, identified as a White Cajun but produced exclusively the Creole-marked \lexi{li} for 3sg.F.
  Likewise, James Corporon identified as a Black Creole but produced exclusively the Cajun-marked \lexi{ils} for 3pl.
  To get a more fine-grained understanding of such situations, social network analysis has proven effective in previous studies.

  Prototypically, social network analysis involves elaborating who is connected to whom, although it can also involve elaborating who is connected to what or what is connected to what.\footnote{
    Social network analysis is in fact an area of the more general network analysis, which is itself simply the applied version of the branch of mathematics called graph theory \parencite{barnes_graph_1983}.
  }
  In doing so, one obtains a direct view of quantifiable social structure.
  Social positions become observable rather than inferred.
  In the case of those whose identities have been racialized, certain social structures are expected that social network analysis can test.
  For Creoles and Cajuns, the objective was to determine if Creoles were connected primarily to Creoles and Cajuns to Cajuns, or in other words, whether personal networks were ethnically homophilous, as this would have explanatory power for the subject pronoun patterns uncovered in the previous chapter.
  In the process, a better understanding of participants' social structures was also uncovered.
  
  % There is evidence that language variation is related to social segregation between the groups involved \parencite{duncan_residential_2018, kohn_segregation_2018}.

  \section{Social network analysis in sociolinguistics}
    \label{sec:sna_sociolinguistics}
    The fundamental focus on interaction in social network analysis has been understood as important in linguistics as a predictor of how one will speak long before the methodology was implemented into the field \parencite[pp.~46-47]{bloomfield_language_1933}.
    This idea has been brought up again and again as an explanation for individuals' linguistic behavior, including when racial barriers are crossed \parencite{sweetland_unexpected_2002}.
    The social network approach to analyzing social structure is appealing enough that it has even been invoked when no network measures are actually implemented \parencite{hoffman_ethnolects_2010, sneller_gritty_2024}.
    % L. Milroy (1980/1987) famously found that social network positions can explain why two speakers from the same community with the same characteristics in terms of social variables might still speak differently (131-134)
    % Gal (1979) argued that not all interactions are the same (15)

    What makes social network analysis so appealing in sociolinguistics is that its quantificational nature fits neatly into traditional variationist methods.
    In particular, it is useful for examining the spread (\foreign{i.e.}, diffusion) of linguistic features \parencite[pp.~262-263]{dodsworth_speech_2014}.
    Diffusion was in fact a central focus early on in sociology, where social network analysis was developed, especially when considering how the closeness of connections (\foreign{i.e.}, the strength of ties) impacts the spread of information \parencite{granovetter_strength_1973, milgram_small-world_1967}.
    The role of race in this diffusion was also regularly present \parencite{korte_acquaintance_1970}.
    Early studies of language change posited that diffusion between groups occurs across strong ties or specifically when individuals have many ties both in and out of a group (\citeauthor{downes_language_1984}, \citeyear[p.~155]{downes_language_1984}; \citeauthor{labov_social_1980}, \citeyear[p.~261]{labov_social_1980}), contrary to arguments for the mechanics of diffusion that had been made in sociology.
    The network data that is needed to examine diffusion directly is quite difficult to collect, however, making linguistics studies that would resolve the diffusion question few and far between.
