    While \textcite{milroy_language_1987} was not the first sociolinguist to actively attempt to bring social network analysis into the field from sociology -- that honor arguably goes to \textcite{gal_language_1979} -- her work has clearly been the most influential in terms of methodology.
    The major theoretical contribution that her study had was the finding that a speaker's lack of integration into a community (\foreign{i.e.}, their centrality) can explain their linguistic difference from that community when broad demographic categories would otherwise predict that they would adhere to that community's norms.
    \textcite{milroy_language_1987} measured centrality with a 5-point index where points were tabulated for facts such as working with two people in the community or spending leisure time with those people (pp.~139/141-142).
    Numerous such indices have been used since then in sociolinguistics with similar results \parencite{cheshire_present_1978, lippi-green_social_1989}.
    Some of this work has focused on race \parencite{ash_linguistic_1986, edwards_sociolinguistic_1992}.
    In the case of \textcite{edwards_sociolinguistic_1992}, one of the index questions asked of his Black participants was whether they often interacted with Whites or not.
    The results of his analysis thus suggest that a lack of interaction between races leads to differences in speech patterns.
    
    Importantly, though, these indices are not generalizable in the sense of being equally applicable to all datasets.
    When \textcite{feagin_competing_1986} tried to apply Milroy's index as-is, the results were quite difficult to interpret.
    As \textcite{lippi-green_social_1989} argued, these indices are idiosyncratic and therefore need to be adapted to each community (p.~218).
    The sort of broad structural data that is required to employ generalizable centrality measures from sociology is rare in sociolinguistics outside of studies of online networks \parencite{kim_sociolinguistic_2014, mcneill_lol_2018, paolillo_virtual_1999}, making indices a necessary compromise.

    Another social network analysis that is more easily carried out and has more often dealt with ethnicity and race is personal network analysis, which centers on particular individuals (\foreign{i.e.}, egos) and elaborates only the ties to other individuals who are connected to these egos at some defined distance (\foreign{i.e.}, alters) without worrying about their position in the overall community (\citeauthor{bott_family_1971}, \citeyear[p.~250]{bott_family_1971}; \citeauthor{perry_egocentric_2018}, \citeyear[p.~6]{perry_egocentric_2018}).
    Such analyses involve examining the characteristics of alters, sometimes relative to the characteristics of egos.
    Perhaps the most common way this is done is by looking at homophily, that is the likeness between egos and their alters on some characteristic \parencite[p.~23]{lazarsfeld_friendship_1954}.
    In sociolinguistics, some of the most robust network analyses have taken this approach.
    For example, \textcite{gal_language_1979} found that the composite peasantness of participants' personal network alters was more predictive of their language choices than their own peasantness, while \textcite{stoessel_investigating_2002} found that immigrants were more likely to maintain their heritage language if they had more speakers of that language in their personal network and if those speakers were in physically close proximity.
    % When a distinction needs to be made between homophily as a mechanism and as a result, the mechanism might be referred to more specifically as selective mixing \parencite[p.~105]{goodreau_birds_2009}.
      % The distinction may be important at times because homophily need not be arrived at only by a tie forming between two individuals who were alike before the fact but may also be arrived at by two individuals becoming more alike after a tie forms between them \parencite[p.~37]{lazarsfeld_friendship_1954}.

    The ethnic homophily of one's network has been found to influence their language in several ways, one of which is in language choice.
    This has especially been a focus of studies of immigrant groups and their offspring.
    In England, members of Chinese families were found to choose Chinese with interlocutors when their personal networks were more Chinese \parencite{li_two-step_2000}, and members of Punjabi families were also more likely to use Punjabi or Urdu when their personal networks included more Punjabis (\citeauthor{reynolds_punjabiurdu_2002}, \citeyear{reynolds_punjabiurdu_2002}; \citeauthor{sharma_scalar_2017}, \citeyear[p.~406]{sharma_scalar_2017}).
    Similar results were found in Norway where Filipino immigrants with higher the ethnic homophily in their personal networks were more likely to use Filipino languages with their children \parencite{lanza_tell_2007}.
    This pattern not has also held when looking at colonial rather than immigrant contexts.
    For example, in the small Pacific country of Palau, participants with more Japanese alters were found to be more likely to use Japanese, a former colonial language \parencite{matsumoto_role_2010}.
    This colonial context especially is suggestive of Louisiana and racialization in general, although the context is not identical.
    In Palau, the break with Japan occurred more recently, during World War II, and so some of the intermarried families had a parent who returned to Japan at that time and only came back later.
    Migratory patterns like those in Palau could have occurred shortly after the Louisiana Purchase in Louisiana, but it is unlikely for many families in the state to still hold such close ties with France or any other French-speaking nation outside of Louisiana today.
    % Within Dyirbal-English speaking communities, the amount of Dyirbal used in casual conversation was relative to the usage of the least monolingual Dyirbal speaker in the group (Schmidt 1985, as cited in L. Milroy 1980/1987:176)
      % Doesn't seem to be related to race or ethnicity, though

    Ethnic homophily has also been seen as important for variation within language, several studies of which have examined groups in New York City.
    Although these two samples were small, the Irish immigrants who maintained the Irish variant of English /t/ were those who had more Irish alters in their network \parencite{kirke_when_2005}, and Chinese-Americans with more ethnic homophily in their networks did not use the local New York variant of English /ɔ/ that those with low ethnic homophily did use \parencite{wong_new_2010}.
    However, in the UK, Polish immigrants to Edinburgh had the proportion of Polish alters in their networks as a significant effect on their realization of English (ing) but not Polish immigrants in London \parencite{schleef_teenagers_2011}.
    It would seem that while ethnic homophily in one's network tends to be a meaningful predictor of language variation, other circumstances can override the effect.
    This is further supported by the finding that higher ``Asianness'' in the personal networks of Punjabis west of London led to great use of [ʈ] for English /t/ only in the middle generation of those who were examined \parencite[pp.~418-419]{sharma_cognitive_2011}.
    In comparing each of these cases to the situation in Louisiana, caution needs to be taken, though.
    Much like the different stages of post-colonialism in which Palau and Louisiana find themselves, the studies mentioned here all involve relatively recent immigration and the navigation of identity around that fact, whereas speakers of F\&C in Louisiana have no need to find a balance between local norms and their heritage as their heritage in fact represents the local norm.
