    A social context that is perhaps more congruent with that of Creoles and Cajuns in Louisiana is that of Blacks and Whites in the US as this implicates racialization, which while not absent from the previously discussed studies -- \textcite{sharma_cognitive_2011} did describe early Punjabi immigrants as facing racial issues rather than ethnic (pp.~405-406) -- the groups that were examined were generally conceptualized as ethnic groups only, but like those ethnic studies, the results for studies of race in the US have not shown consistent effects for personal network racial homophily.
    \textcite{labov_facto_1986}, for instance, looked at a slightly extended personal network for Eddie, a Black man in North Philadelphia, and concluded that the morphological patterns of those in his network were better explained by their social histories rather than by the network.
    However, they did not employ any network measures but rather directly interpreted the sociograms (\foreign{i.e.}, network diagrams) that they drew.
    In fact, their data collection methods were not shared, making it difficult to understand what may be missing or present from those sociograms in the first place.
    Their conclusion was supported, though, by a longitudinal study of African-American youths in Chapel Hill, North Carolina where the number of African-American social contacts of participants did not have a significant effect on the rate of usage of African-American English features.
    This result, again, was unfortunately rather opaque as no descriptive statistics were provided for the proportion of African-Americans that participants actually had in their networks as it would not be unusual for all participants to have rather high racially homophilous networks.
    Instead, only the regression model was provided.
    This does not mean that these results, that young African-Americans in Chapel Hill and Black speakers in North Philadelphia are not sensitive to the racial make-up of their networks, but they should perhaps be considered with care.

    Other studies of race in the US, in contrast, have shown effects for racial homophily.
    African-Americans in Memphis who had higher rates of racial homophily in their networks were found to be more involved in the southern vowel shift than those with more racially diverse networks \parencite{fridland_network_2003}.
    Unfortunately, this sample was limited to 10 participants, so not statistical analyses were used to establish this pattern.
    A larger study, however, was conducted in Philadelphia, just as in \citeauthor{labov_facto_1986}'s (\citeyear{labov_facto_1986}) work, and found that Black speakers with less racially homophilous networks use more linguistic features associated with Black speakers then others.
    Likewise, White speakers in the data with little contact with Black speakers used fewer Black linguistic features, although White participants constituted a minority of the sample \parencite{ash_linguistic_1986}.
    This has perhaps been the most transparent and robust study of the impact of homophily on racially-marked language use as the sample included 28 speakers for whom homophily was calculated rather than inferred and whose homophily rates ranged from very high to very low.
    Where racialized social systems are in place, in fact, one should probably not expect to find low racial homophily in the first place.
    If participants who have low racial homophily in their personal networks are outliers, it is not surprising that studies of language variation are sometimes unable to show significant effects for the \emph{amount} of racial homophily, but this does not necessarily mean that racial homophily is not an important factor.
