    In Louisiana specifically, while there is a long and continuing history of racial segregation that has been examined at the community level (see Section \ref{sec:united_states}), there is a dearth of examinations on what personal networks look like racially in Louisiana.
    This is true whether dealing with Creole racialization or the broader categories of Black and White, and it is especially true in sociolinguistics.
    While sociolinguistic ethnographic work on Creoles has taken place in Louisiana \parencite{wendte_tale_2020}, quantitative network analyses have been absent.
    Only one study, outside of sociolinguistics, has addressed how the racial make-up of personal networks relate to Creoles, in this case in terms of how they view their Creole identities.
    It was found that those Creoles of color who racially identified as singular Black had mostly Black friends, whereas those who racially identified as border Creole (\foreign{i.e.}, a stable mixed identity) had mostly White friends, and those who identified as protean (\foreign{i.e.}, racially shifting) had a relatively even racial mix of friends \parencite[pp.~45/48]{susberry_racial_2004}.

    The current study aims to add to this picture by looking not at the Black and White composition of personal network but the Creole and Cajun composition relative to individuals who self-identify as Creole or Cajun themselves and how this impacts language use.
    Specifically, the primary research question is the following:
    \begin{itemize}
      \item[RQ:] How does the homophily or lack thereof in the ethnic make-up of personal networks among F\&C speakers in South Louisiana relate to variation in subject pronoun usage?
    \end{itemize}
    Along the way, useful descriptive details about the social structures surrounding Creoles and Cajuns will be presented.

